    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-08T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-08T22:00:00-05:00" n="927"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d927">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00 Revolutions/325: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Burdett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-08T22:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 8, 1932—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 9—12:03 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>98. Seven hundred troops now on the way to <persName corresp="#p_TMGRL1"
                        >Trujillo</persName>. Government has officially closed ports of Salaverry,
                    Puerto Chicama, Huanchaco which are in the hands of the rebels.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HTA1">Augustin Haya de la Torre</persName> has telegraphed
                    Government threatening to excute prisoners unless his brother now imprisoned in
                    Lima is released.</p>
                <p>Thirty-five American citizens are in <persName corresp="#p_TMGRL1"
                        >Trujillo</persName> district mostly in Cartavio, Grace sugar estate.
                    Communications are cut off with the entire district but all Americans believed
                    to be safe. Movement is anti-<persName corresp="#p_SCCLM1">Sanchez
                        Cerro</persName> not anti-foreign. Lima relatively quiet, south quiet.
                    Developments depend upon the doubtful loyalty of the Army, Navy and Aviation
                    service.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Burdett</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
